    <div class="finance-container">
        <p><strong>Overview:</strong> In India, project financing is crucial for achieving long-term sustainability in infrastructure, healthcare, education, and technology. Below are the details about ongoing, upcoming, and completed projects, their financing, and how funds are allocated to ensure successful project execution.</p>

        <h3>Types of Projects and Key Funding Sources</h3>
        <p>India's diverse needs in various sectors require tailored financing solutions. Here's an overview of the key project types and their funding sources:</p>
        
        <div class="projects-section">
            <div class="project-category">
                <h4>1. Infrastructure Projects</h4>
                <p>Funding for infrastructure projects like highways, airports, and power plants typically involves a mix of government grants, PPPs, and commercial bank loans.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="project-category">
                <h4>2. Social Welfare Projects</h4>
                <p>Projects in healthcare, education, and rural development are often funded through government grants, CSR contributions, and foreign aid.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="project-category">
                <h4>3. Innovation and Technology</h4>
                <p>These projects are driven by private investments, venture capital, and government innovation funds. They focus on digital infrastructure, renewable energy, and smart city initiatives.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Funding Process & Key Stakeholders</h3>
        <p>Securing project financing involves a detailed process with several key stakeholders:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Feasibility Study & Proposal:</strong> Detailed analysis of the project's potential and viability. Involves project managers, consultants, and government agencies.</li>
            <li><strong>Initial Funding:</strong> Government departments, private investors, and financial institutions allocate funds at the start of the project.</li>
            <li><strong>Progress Monitoring:</strong> As the project progresses, funds are disbursed in phases based on milestones and government approvals.</li>
            <li><strong>Final Evaluation:</strong> Upon project completion, financial assessments ensure that allocated funds are effectively utilized and not overspent.</li>
        </ol>

